    "speaker": "interviewee",
    "tag": "MP",
    "text": "My dear children, grandchildren, and future generations who come into our family, let me give you a little background. In 1939, the war between Germany and Poland had started. Your baba, your grandma Lucy, was then 11 years old. Your zaide, Murray, grandfather, was 14 years old. Your grandma went to Siberia, lost her father when she was only 12 years old, and had to go through all kind of hell to be, to be alive. Your grandfather, your zaide, was in a few concentration camps, lost his entire family and survived because of a miracle that Oskar Schindler-- I was on Schindler's list. In 1949, we came to America. We started a new life. In '49, we were fortunate enough to have our first son born, then in '51, our daughter, and in '57, our younger daughter, Larry, Betty, and Elisa. And you got married. And you really going through the family that you always would be together. The cousins, I have nine grandchildren. You have-- each one of you have eight cousins. You should be together. There's nothing, anything stronger than a family. And I have a request that every time you're making a bar mitzvah, or bat mitzvah, or you're marrying off a child, and you're bringing in a new person in the family, that they should understand how precious and how hard it, it was for us to raise this family. I wish you all the luck in the world. And remember above everything, you must be a mensch. You have to respect your fellow man. Thank you. And God bless you. And best wishes from baba Lucy and zaide Murray.",
